{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Do focused WEB research (WebSearch + WebFetch; cite URLs) for a safety-critical timing decision in a local self-evolving agent (\"Yogi\", Rust, single 16 GB Apple Silicon Mac). Do not answer from memory alone.\n\nCONTEXT: Yogi's operator-owned \"supervisor\" (budget authority + reaper + kill-switch) is currently an IN-PROCESS Rust module behind a narrow trait (a reference monitor). An earlier decision set a HARD GATE: \"move the supervisor to a separate OS process (privilege separation) + a Wasmtime/WASM capability sandbox for tool/executor code BEFORE M4 self-modification lands OR before any model-generated/native code executes — whichever comes first.\"\n\nTHE NUANCE TO RESOLVE: M4's self-modification is BOUNDED and DECLARATIVE — the being edits only closed-enum genome fields (prompt/policy strings, skill ids) via a pure `apply()` function. It does NOT execute arbitrary or model-generated code at M4. Arbitrary/tool code execution comes LATER (the executor running tools). So: does bounded declarative self-mod actually require the full process-split + WASM upgrade NOW, or is the in-process reference monitor still honest until the executor runs untrusted/model-generated code?\n\nResearch:\n1. **Reference-monitor / tamper-proof criteria** (NIST, Anderson): is in-process \"tamper-proof\" violated by code that only mutates declarative data it doesn't execute? When precisely does in-process stop being honest — at \"self-modification\" generally, or specifically at \"in-address-space execution of attacker/model-influenced code\"?\n2. **Privilege separation in practice** (OpenSSH-style): what threat does a separate-process monitor actually defend against, and is that threat present when the supervised code can't execute arbitrary instructions?\n3. **WASM/Wasmtime sandboxing on macOS for Rust:** practical cost/complexity of (a) splitting the supervisor into a separate process with IPC, and (b) running tool/executor code in Wasmtime with fuel/epoch limits and capability imports. What's the minimum that holds, and what's overkill for a single-machine research build?\n4. **Staging:** is there a principled \"trigger\" formulation — e.g. \"upgrade to process-split + WASM the moment the executor runs any model-generated or external-tool code, not before\" — that keeps M4's declarative self-mod safe in-process while honestly committing to the upgrade at the real boundary?\n\nEND WITH a concrete RECOMMENDATION: should Yogi do the isolation upgrade NOW (before M4 declarative self-mod) or defer it to the executor/tool-execution step, with a precise written trigger? If defer, state exactly what M4 must NOT do to remain honest in-process. Cite URLs throughout. Return findings only; do not edit files."},"uuid":"e15853ef-f760-44d3-9936-8e6040ec0ccb","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:09.511Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
