{"parentUuid":"52caed40-6101-49f0-b345-1f4d09bea19e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YZbAH3DrXgxoFEP1QaGaAd","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"reference monitor tamper-proof verifiable nonbypassable NIST Anderson security kernel definition\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Reference monitor — Grokipedia\",\"url\":\"https://grokipedia.com/page/Reference_monitor\"},{\"title\":\"Reference monitor - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reference_monitor\"},{\"title\":\"Reference Monitor | Springer Nature Link\",\"url\":\"https://link.springer.com/rwe/10.1007/978-1-4419-5906-5_646\"},{\"title\":\"security kernel - Glossary | CSRC\",\"url\":\"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/security_kernel\"},{\"title\":\"Understanding CISSP Domain 3: Security Architecture and Engineering - Part 1\",\"url\":\"https://blog.balancedsec.com/p/understanding-cissp-domain-3-security\"},{\"title\":\"Orange Book Parts I and II: THE CRITERIA and RATIONALE AND GUIDELINES: RATIONALE BEHIND THE EVALUATION CLASSES\",\"url\":\"https://www.kernel.org/pub/linux/libs/security/Orange-Linux/refs/Orange/OrangeI-II-6.html\"},{\"title\":\"Security Architecture and Design/Systems Security Architecture - Wikibooks, open books for an open world\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Security_Architecture_and_Design/Systems_Security_Architecture\"},{\"title\":\"Access control differentiation in trusted computer system\",\"url\":\"https://image-ppubs.uspto.gov/dirsearch-public/print/downloadPdf/7765595\"},{\"title\":\"A Comprehensive Survey on the State-of-the-art Data Provenance   Approaches for Security Enforcement\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2107.01678\"},{\"title\":\"Trusted computer system\",\"url\":\"https://image-ppubs.uspto.gov/dirsearch-public/print/downloadPdf/7103914\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found regarding reference monitors, tamper-proof verification, and the security kernel definition from Anderson and NIST:\n\n## Anderson's Reference Monitor Concept\n\nAnderson defined the reference validation mechanism as validating each reference to data or programs against authorized types for that user, requiring it to be tamper proof, always be invoked, and be small enough for analysis and tests with assured completeness.\n\n## Key Properties (NEAT)\n\nThe essential requirements are that the mechanism must be non-bypassable, always invoked, tamper-proof, and evaluable to ensure correct operation—a set of properties often remembered by the acronym NEAT: Non-bypassable (the mechanism cannot be circumvented), Evaluable/Verifiable (correctness must be verifiable through analysis and testing), Always invoked (activated for every access attempt), and Tamper-proof/Isolation (protected from alteration).\n\n## NIST Definition of Security Kernel\n\nNIST defines the security kernel as hardware, firmware, and software elements of a trusted computing base implementing the reference monitor concept, and it must mediate all accesses, be protected from modification, and be verifiable as correct.\n\n## Reference Monitor in NIST Standards\n\nNIST embedded reference monitor concepts into its Security and Privacy Controls for Information Systems and Organizations (SP 800-53), where control AC-25 explicitly requires implementation of a reference monitor to enforce access policies through a tamper-evident mechanism.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"a34d5457-6bdd-4b97-a443-8b6564d8b54f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:28.615Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"reference monitor tamper-proof verifiable nonbypassable NIST Anderson security kernel definition","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_011SC9qEKT8oJmxt8Ce4f7bU","content":[{"title":"Reference monitor — Grokipedia","url":"https://grokipedia.com/page/Reference_monitor"},{"title":"Reference monitor - Wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reference_monitor"},{"title":"Reference Monitor | Springer Nature Link","url":"https://link.springer.com/rwe/10.1007/978-1-4419-5906-5_646"},{"title":"security kernel - Glossary | CSRC","url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/security_kernel"},{"title":"Understanding CISSP Domain 3: Security Architecture and Engineering - Part 1","url":"https://blog.balancedsec.com/p/understanding-cissp-domain-3-security"},{"title":"Orange Book Parts I and II: THE CRITERIA and RATIONALE AND GUIDELINES: RATIONALE BEHIND THE EVALUATION CLASSES","url":"https://www.kernel.org/pub/linux/libs/security/Orange-Linux/refs/Orange/OrangeI-II-6.html"},{"title":"Security Architecture and Design/Systems Security Architecture - Wikibooks, open books for an open world","url":"https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Security_Architecture_and_Design/Systems_Security_Architecture"},{"title":"Access control differentiation in trusted computer system","url":"https://image-ppubs.uspto.gov/dirsearch-public/print/downloadPdf/7765595"},{"title":"A Comprehensive Survey on the State-of-the-art Data Provenance   Approaches for Security Enforcement","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2107.01678"},{"title":"Trusted computer system","url":"https://image-ppubs.uspto.gov/dirsearch-public/print/downloadPdf/7103914"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding reference monitors, tamper-proof verification, and the security kernel definition from Anderson and NIST:\n\n## Anderson's Reference Monitor Concept\n\nAnderson defined the reference validation mechanism as validating each reference to data or programs against authorized types for that user, requiring it to be tamper proof, always be invoked, and be small enough for analysis and tests with assured completeness.\n\n## Key Properties (NEAT)\n\nThe essential requirements are that the mechanism must be non-bypassable, always invoked, tamper-proof, and evaluable to ensure correct operation—a set of properties often remembered by the acronym NEAT: Non-bypassable (the mechanism cannot be circumvented), Evaluable/Verifiable (correctness must be verifiable through analysis and testing), Always invoked (activated for every access attempt), and Tamper-proof/Isolation (protected from alteration).\n\n## NIST Definition of Security Kernel\n\nNIST defines the security kernel as hardware, firmware, and software elements of a trusted computing base implementing the reference monitor concept, and it must mediate all accesses, be protected from modification, and be verifiable as correct.\n\n## Reference Monitor in NIST Standards\n\nNIST embedded reference monitor concepts into its Security and Privacy Controls for Information Systems and Organizations (SP 800-53), where control AC-25 explicitly requires implementation of a reference monitor to enforce access policies through a tamper-evident mechanism."],"durationSeconds":8.361261416000081,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"52caed40-6101-49f0-b345-1f4d09bea19e","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"44d931e9-7865-435d-9ad0-45162f95ebdf","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Ec5d7EZHo8nQ7u2a4GXuc8","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"OpenSSH privilege separation design threat model separate process Provos\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"CITI Technical Report 02-2 Preventing Privilege Escalation Niels Provos\",\"url\":\"http://citi.umich.edu/techreports/reports/citi-tr-02-2.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Towards Automated Privilege Separation\",\"url\":\"https://www.cise.ufl.edu/~butler/pubs/iciss07.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Privilege Separated OpenSSH\",\"url\":\"http://www.citi.umich.edu/u/provos/ssh/privsep.html\"},{\"title\":\"Preventing Privilege Escalation Niels Provos CITI, University of Michigan\",\"url\":\"http://www.citi.umich.edu/u/provos/papers/privsep.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Examining OpenSSH Sandboxing and Privilege Separation - Attack Surface Analysis\",\"url\":\"https://jfrog.com/blog/examining-openssh-sandboxing-and-privilege-separation-attack-surface-analysis/\"},{\"title\":\"openssh-portable/README.privsep at master · openssh/openssh-portable\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/openssh/openssh-portable/blob/master/README.privsep\"},{\"title\":\"[SOLVED] OpenSSH Privilege Separation\",\"url\":\"https://www.linuxquestions.org/questions/slackware-14/openssh-privilege-separation-4175572689/\"},{\"title\":\"Privtrans: Automatically Partitioning Programs for Privilege Separation\",\"url\":\"https://dawnsong.io/papers/privtrans.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Privilege separation - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Privilege_separation\"}]\n\nI've found search results related to OpenSSH privilege separation design. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Overview of OpenSSH Privilege Separation\n\nPrivilege separation (privsep) is a method in OpenSSH by which operations that require root privilege are performed by a separate privileged monitor process, with the purpose of preventing privilege escalation by containing corruption to an unprivileged process.\n\n## Architecture\n\nPrivilege separation uses two processes: the privileged parent process that monitors the progress of the unprivileged child process, and the child process which is unprivileged. An unprivileged slave processes all network communication and must ask the monitor to perform any operation.\n\n## Threat Model and Security Goal\n\nThe goal of privilege separation is to make sure pre-authentication attacks cannot compromise the root account even though other parts of OpenSSH do run with root privileges. By performing the authentication in the parent process, OpenSSH is able to ensure that sensitive authentication data never leaves the privileged process, which provides an additional layer of security.\n\n## Provos' Work\n\nProvos et al. manually separated the privileged part of the OpenSSH program from the less privileged part, requiring considerable effort. Provos et al. manually added privilege separation to OpenSSH version 3.1p1, with the privilege separated code available as OpenSSH version 3.2.2p1.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"549f326d-ca7a-4d37-82d6-c16968c2198e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:29.095Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"OpenSSH privilege separation design threat model separate process Provos","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01BGzMLVwHYkkACArd9tKbHg","content":[{"title":"CITI Technical Report 02-2 Preventing Privilege Escalation Niels Provos","url":"http://citi.umich.edu/techreports/reports/citi-tr-02-2.pdf"},{"title":"Towards Automated Privilege Separation","url":"https://www.cise.ufl.edu/~butler/pubs/iciss07.pdf"},{"title":"Privilege Separated OpenSSH","url":"http://www.citi.umich.edu/u/provos/ssh/privsep.html"},{"title":"Preventing Privilege Escalation Niels Provos CITI, University of Michigan","url":"http://www.citi.umich.edu/u/provos/papers/privsep.pdf"},{"title":"Examining OpenSSH Sandboxing and Privilege Separation - Attack Surface Analysis","url":"https://jfrog.com/blog/examining-openssh-sandboxing-and-privilege-separation-attack-surface-analysis/"},{"title":"openssh-portable/README.privsep at master · openssh/openssh-portable","url":"https://github.com/openssh/openssh-portable/blob/master/README.privsep"},{"title":"[SOLVED] OpenSSH Privilege Separation","url":"https://www.linuxquestions.org/questions/slackware-14/openssh-privilege-separation-4175572689/"},{"title":"Privtrans: Automatically Partitioning Programs for Privilege Separation","url":"https://dawnsong.io/papers/privtrans.pdf"},{"title":"Privilege separation - Wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Privilege_separation"}]},"I've found search results related to OpenSSH privilege separation design. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Overview of OpenSSH Privilege Separation\n\nPrivilege separation (privsep) is a method in OpenSSH by which operations that require root privilege are performed by a separate privileged monitor process, with the purpose of preventing privilege escalation by containing corruption to an unprivileged process.\n\n## Architecture\n\nPrivilege separation uses two processes: the privileged parent process that monitors the progress of the unprivileged child process, and the child process which is unprivileged. An unprivileged slave processes all network communication and must ask the monitor to perform any operation.\n\n## Threat Model and Security Goal\n\nThe goal of privilege separation is to make sure pre-authentication attacks cannot compromise the root account even though other parts of OpenSSH do run with root privileges. By performing the authentication in the parent process, OpenSSH is able to ensure that sensitive authentication data never leaves the privileged process, which provides an additional layer of security.\n\n## Provos' Work\n\nProvos et al. manually separated the privileged part of the OpenSSH program from the less privileged part, requiring considerable effort. Provos et al. manually added privilege separation to OpenSSH version 3.1p1, with the privilege separated code available as OpenSSH version 3.2.2p1."],"durationSeconds":7.8948854159999176,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"44d931e9-7865-435d-9ad0-45162f95ebdf","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"0d163e98-9e90-4f32-8dac-6c8a3741b498","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019PhdYSMm48YpBN39AhiwoT","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Wasmtime Rust embedding fuel epoch interruption capability WASI sandbox cost\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Config in wasmtime - Rust\",\"url\":\"https://docs.wasmtime.dev/api/wasmtime/struct.Config.html\"},{\"title\":\"Wasmtime's embedding API\",\"url\":\"https://docs.wasmtime.dev/api/wasmtime/\"},{\"title\":\"wasmtime - Rust\",\"url\":\"https://docs.rs/wasmtime\"},{\"title\":\"config.rs - source\",\"url\":\"https://docs.wasmtime.dev/api/src/wasmtime/config.rs.html\"},{\"title\":\"Wasmtime In-Depth Tutorial | wasmRuntime.com\",\"url\":\"https://wasmruntime.com/en/tutorials/wasmtime\"},{\"title\":\"Python + Wasmtime in Servers: Safe Sandbox for Untrusted UDFs at Near-Native Speed | by Codastra | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@2nick2patel2/python-wasmtime-in-servers-safe-sandbox-for-untrusted-udfs-at-near-native-speed-ed858be1c48e\"},{\"title\":\"WebAssembly and Unikernels: A Comparative Study for Serverless at the Edge\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.09400v1\"},{\"title\":\"Security - Wasmtime\",\"url\":\"https://docs.wasmtime.dev/security.html\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about Wasmtime's Rust embedding capabilities regarding fuel, epoch interruption, WASI sandbox, and cost:\n\n## Epoch-Based Interruption\n\nEpoch-based interruption is a lightweight mechanism for interrupting long-running WebAssembly code. Fuel instrumentation is somewhat expensive because it modifies compiled Wasm code to maintain a precise instruction count, but if you don't need this precise count or deterministic interruptions and only need periodic interrupts, epoch-based interruption is better.\n\n## Fuel-Based Cost Control\n\nYou can enable Config::consume_fuel along with Store::fuel_async_yield_interval to configure Wasmtime futures to yield periodically while executing WebAssembly code, with futures returning Poll::Pending after consuming the specified amount of fuel. Unlike epoch-based preemption, fuel consumption is deterministic since wasm always consumes a fixed amount of fuel per-operation, though the compiled code instrumentation is significantly more expensive than epoch checks.\n\n## Performance Comparison\n\nIn general, epoch-based interruption results in faster execution compared to fuel-based approaches.\n\n## WASI Sandbox & Capabilities\n\nThe wasmtime crate doesn't natively provide WASI support, but the wasmtime-wasi crate can be used, and all WASI functions can be added to a Linker and then used to instantiate WASI-using modules. Wasmtime implements WASI APIs for filesystem access following a capability-based security model, ensuring applications can only access files and directories they've been given access to.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"6ad3cac2-bcfa-4755-8e9a-43f0b7035836","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:32.675Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Wasmtime Rust embedding fuel epoch interruption capability WASI sandbox cost","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_014APmFFTWMFdDLuh4qTqf5S","content":[{"title":"Config in wasmtime - Rust","url":"https://docs.wasmtime.dev/api/wasmtime/struct.Config.html"},{"title":"Wasmtime's embedding API","url":"https://docs.wasmtime.dev/api/wasmtime/"},{"title":"wasmtime - Rust","url":"https://docs.rs/wasmtime"},{"title":"config.rs - source","url":"https://docs.wasmtime.dev/api/src/wasmtime/config.rs.html"},{"title":"Wasmtime In-Depth Tutorial | wasmRuntime.com","url":"https://wasmruntime.com/en/tutorials/wasmtime"},{"title":"Python + Wasmtime in Servers: Safe Sandbox for Untrusted UDFs at Near-Native Speed | by Codastra | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@2nick2patel2/python-wasmtime-in-servers-safe-sandbox-for-untrusted-udfs-at-near-native-speed-ed858be1c48e"},{"title":"WebAssembly and Unikernels: A Comparative Study for Serverless at the Edge","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.09400v1"},{"title":"Security - Wasmtime","url":"https://docs.wasmtime.dev/security.html"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about Wasmtime's Rust embedding capabilities regarding fuel, epoch interruption, WASI sandbox, and cost:\n\n## Epoch-Based Interruption\n\nEpoch-based interruption is a lightweight mechanism for interrupting long-running WebAssembly code. Fuel instrumentation is somewhat expensive because it modifies compiled Wasm code to maintain a precise instruction count, but if you don't need this precise count or deterministic interruptions and only need periodic interrupts, epoch-based interruption is better.\n\n## Fuel-Based Cost Control\n\nYou can enable Config::consume_fuel along with Store::fuel_async_yield_interval to configure Wasmtime futures to yield periodically while executing WebAssembly code, with futures returning Poll::Pending after consuming the specified amount of fuel. Unlike epoch-based preemption, fuel consumption is deterministic since wasm always consumes a fixed amount of fuel per-operation, though the compiled code instrumentation is significantly more expensive than epoch checks.\n\n## Performance Comparison\n\nIn general, epoch-based interruption results in faster execution compared to fuel-based approaches.\n\n## WASI Sandbox & Capabilities\n\nThe wasmtime crate doesn't natively provide WASI support, but the wasmtime-wasi crate can be used, and all WASI functions can be added to a Linker and then used to instantiate WASI-using modules. Wasmtime implements WASI APIs for filesystem access following a capability-based security model, ensuring applications can only access files and directories they've been given access to."],"durationSeconds":11.065917417000048,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"0d163e98-9e90-4f32-8dac-6c8a3741b498","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
