{"parentUuid":"0623ab34-2945-4fd3-9100-0798c51b2f84","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01EHzGDRKbU8xryE1UwLHerY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01LjJwQqZSbC8Frfpk6DMQFP","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reference_monitor","prompt":"What are the three/four requirements of a reference monitor (tamper-proof, always invoked, small/verifiable)? Specifically what does \"tamperproof\" mean — is it about the supervised code being unable to modify the monitor, and is that threat dependent on the supervised code being able to execute arbitrary instructions in the same address space?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4713,"cache_read_input_tokens":12784,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4713,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFkryoyXurqeDwBNqLLp","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"b3180ed0-7caa-4d6a-a69a-5f5c465d77e4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:40.904Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b3180ed0-7caa-4d6a-a69a-5f5c465d77e4","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01EHzGDRKbU8xryE1UwLHerY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_012gcde1XuiwF5Gtxq4xJapf","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"in-process sandbox versus separate process isolation memory safety Rust untrusted code threat boundary"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4713,"cache_read_input_tokens":12784,"output_tokens":503,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4713},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":503,"cache_read_input_tokens":12784,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4713,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4713,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFkryoyXurqeDwBNqLLp","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"5f23a0dc-78e2-4b10-8b29-3ca81da46aa2","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:41.393Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b3180ed0-7caa-4d6a-a69a-5f5c465d77e4","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LjJwQqZSbC8Frfpk6DMQFP","type":"tool_result","content":"# Reference Monitor Requirements\n\nAccording to the Wikipedia article, a reference monitor must satisfy **NEAT** properties:\n\n1. **Non-bypassable**: \"an attacker cannot bypass the mechanism and violate the security policy\"\n2. **Evaluable**: amenable to analysis and testing with verifiable completeness\n3. **Always invoked**: must perform when intended to prevent policy violations\n4. **Tamper-proof**: \"an attacker can undermine the mechanism itself and hence violate the security policy\" if this property fails\n\n## On \"Tamper-proof\"\n\nThe article defines tamper-proof negatively—explaining what happens without it—rather than detailing the specific threat model. It indicates the mechanism itself must resist attacks, but doesn't explicitly address whether this assumes supervised code shares an address space or can execute arbitrary instructions.\n\nThe article notes that while Windows NT was \"designed to contain a reference monitor,\" it's \"not clear that its properties (tamperproof, etc.) have ever been independently verified,\" suggesting tamper-proof verification is non-trivial in practice. However, the source doesn't provide architectural details about the threat scope you're asking about."}]},"uuid":"86f343d3-73fc-4445-854d-2275a0427998","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:45.753Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":69474,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Reference Monitor Requirements\n\nAccording to the Wikipedia article, a reference monitor must satisfy **NEAT** properties:\n\n1. **Non-bypassable**: \"an attacker cannot bypass the mechanism and violate the security policy\"\n2. **Evaluable**: amenable to analysis and testing with verifiable completeness\n3. **Always invoked**: must perform when intended to prevent policy violations\n4. **Tamper-proof**: \"an attacker can undermine the mechanism itself and hence violate the security policy\" if this property fails\n\n## On \"Tamper-proof\"\n\nThe article defines tamper-proof negatively—explaining what happens without it—rather than detailing the specific threat model. It indicates the mechanism itself must resist attacks, but doesn't explicitly address whether this assumes supervised code shares an address space or can execute arbitrary instructions.\n\nThe article notes that while Windows NT was \"designed to contain a reference monitor,\" it's \"not clear that its properties (tamperproof, etc.) have ever been independently verified,\" suggesting tamper-proof verification is non-trivial in practice. However, the source doesn't provide architectural details about the threat scope you're asking about.","durationMs":4684,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reference_monitor"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b3180ed0-7caa-4d6a-a69a-5f5c465d77e4","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"5f23a0dc-78e2-4b10-8b29-3ca81da46aa2","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012gcde1XuiwF5Gtxq4xJapf","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"in-process sandbox versus separate process isolation memory safety Rust untrusted code threat boundary\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Sandcrust: Automatic Sandboxing of Unsafe Components in Rust | Request PDF\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/320748351_Sandcrust_Automatic_Sandboxing_of_Unsafe_Components_in_Rust\"},{\"title\":\"Friend or Foe Inside? Exploring In-Process Isolation to Maintain Memory Safety for Unsafe Rust\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2306.08127v2\"},{\"title\":\"[2306.08127] Friend or Foe Inside? Exploring In-Process Isolation to Maintain Memory Safety for Unsafe Rust\",\"url\":\"https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2306.08127\"},{\"title\":\"Friend or Foe Inside? Exploring In-Process Isolation to Maintain Memory Safety for Unsafe Rust | Request PDF\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/375513319_Friend_or_Foe_Inside_Exploring_In-Process_Isolation_to_Maintain_Memory_Safety_for_Unsafe_Rust\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - corrode/tarnish: Sandbox untrusted Rust code with isolated processes\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/corrode/tarnish\"},{\"title\":\"SandCell: Sandboxing Rust Beyond Unsafe Code\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.24032v1\"},{\"title\":\"TRUST: A Compilation Framework for In-process Isolation ...\",\"url\":\"https://www.usenix.org/system/files/sec23fall-prepub-504-bang.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"TRust: A Compilation Framework for In-process Isolation to Protect Safe Rust against Untrusted Code | USENIX\",\"url\":\"https://www.usenix.org/conference/usenixsecurity23/presentation/bang\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about in-process sandbox versus separate process isolation for memory safety in Rust with untrusted code:\n\n## Key Differences\n\n**Separate Process Isolation:**\n\nProcess-based isolation protects integrity by ensuring each process runs in its own virtual memory space that prevents a malicious process from accessing another process's memory, and provides resilience through separate failure boundaries so one process failure doesn't affect others. However, inter-process communication typically comes with high overheads due to context switching and data crossing security boundaries.\n\nSeparate process isolation can survive crashes that in-process solutions cannot, such as segfaults from unsafe code.\n\n**In-Process Isolation:**\n\nSandCell provides flexible and lightweight isolation in Rust by allowing programmers to specify which components to sandbox with minimal annotation effort, enabling fine-grained control over isolation. TRUST allocates objects in isolated memory regions accessible to safe Rust but restricted from untrusted code, using software fault isolation and x86 protection keys.\n\n## Trade-offs\n\nThe fundamental trade-off is between **security boundary strength** (separate processes provide stronger isolation guarantees) and **performance** (in-process isolation has lower overhead). In-process solutions like TRUST can achieve relatively low overhead, with only 7.55% runtime and 13.30% memory overhead, whereas separate process approaches incur IPC-related costs.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"5e2a823c-36eb-4f0b-bced-c8c1a06c6b04","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:51.630Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"in-process sandbox versus separate process isolation memory safety Rust untrusted code threat boundary","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Nq7iLMnJJi65AizV1aUaFt","content":[{"title":"Sandcrust: Automatic Sandboxing of Unsafe Components in Rust | Request PDF","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/320748351_Sandcrust_Automatic_Sandboxing_of_Unsafe_Components_in_Rust"},{"title":"Friend or Foe Inside? Exploring In-Process Isolation to Maintain Memory Safety for Unsafe Rust","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2306.08127v2"},{"title":"[2306.08127] Friend or Foe Inside? Exploring In-Process Isolation to Maintain Memory Safety for Unsafe Rust","url":"https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2306.08127"},{"title":"Friend or Foe Inside? Exploring In-Process Isolation to Maintain Memory Safety for Unsafe Rust | Request PDF","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/375513319_Friend_or_Foe_Inside_Exploring_In-Process_Isolation_to_Maintain_Memory_Safety_for_Unsafe_Rust"},{"title":"GitHub - corrode/tarnish: Sandbox untrusted Rust code with isolated processes","url":"https://github.com/corrode/tarnish"},{"title":"SandCell: Sandboxing Rust Beyond Unsafe Code","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.24032v1"},{"title":"TRUST: A Compilation Framework for In-process Isolation ...","url":"https://www.usenix.org/system/files/sec23fall-prepub-504-bang.pdf"},{"title":"TRust: A Compilation Framework for In-process Isolation to Protect Safe Rust against Untrusted Code | USENIX","url":"https://www.usenix.org/conference/usenixsecurity23/presentation/bang"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about in-process sandbox versus separate process isolation for memory safety in Rust with untrusted code:\n\n## Key Differences\n\n**Separate Process Isolation:**\n\nProcess-based isolation protects integrity by ensuring each process runs in its own virtual memory space that prevents a malicious process from accessing another process's memory, and provides resilience through separate failure boundaries so one process failure doesn't affect others. However, inter-process communication typically comes with high overheads due to context switching and data crossing security boundaries.\n\nSeparate process isolation can survive crashes that in-process solutions cannot, such as segfaults from unsafe code.\n\n**In-Process Isolation:**\n\nSandCell provides flexible and lightweight isolation in Rust by allowing programmers to specify which components to sandbox with minimal annotation effort, enabling fine-grained control over isolation. TRUST allocates objects in isolated memory regions accessible to safe Rust but restricted from untrusted code, using software fault isolation and x86 protection keys.\n\n## Trade-offs\n\nThe fundamental trade-off is between **security boundary strength** (separate processes provide stronger isolation guarantees) and **performance** (in-process isolation has lower overhead). In-process solutions like TRUST can achieve relatively low overhead, with only 7.55% runtime and 13.30% memory overhead, whereas separate process approaches incur IPC-related costs."],"durationSeconds":10.047857874999988,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"5f23a0dc-78e2-4b10-8b29-3ca81da46aa2","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
