{"parentUuid":"e7420e8c-938f-4e31-aa40-eceb878cbe56","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_014FF12bHyjPxrzU4KrEd8Co","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01LK8qkeyYmqAKS1adpQZV36","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Privilege_separation","prompt":"What specific threat does privilege separation defend against? Is the protection relevant only when the unprivileged/supervised process can be compromised into running attacker-controlled code (e.g. via memory corruption / code injection / exploited bug)? Does privilege separation provide any benefit if the supervised code cannot execute arbitrary instructions at all?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1967,"cache_creation_input_tokens":547,"cache_read_input_tokens":17497,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":547,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFkwuYtJSNj6vFrcJvur","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"c164eccf-e8ae-4ac4-8348-286ede383edf","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:16:44.106Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"c164eccf-e8ae-4ac4-8348-286ede383edf","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_014FF12bHyjPxrzU4KrEd8Co","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_014pirFZWFf5HGaxR1223Cfr","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://docs.wasmtime.dev/security.html","prompt":"What is Wasmtime's security/sandboxing model? What does it protect against (untrusted/compiled WebAssembly code), and what are its assumptions and known limitations on a host like macOS? Summarize what threats Wasmtime is designed to contain and when you would need it."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1967,"cache_creation_input_tokens":547,"cache_read_input_tokens":17497,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":547,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFkwuYtJSNj6vFrcJvur","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"0bf569a0-8f13-4354-9b5f-64246bf3784d","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:16:46.403Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"0bf569a0-8f13-4354-9b5f-64246bf3784d","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_014FF12bHyjPxrzU4KrEd8Co","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Cri4cQxsxPqVvr9aspsD2E","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"capability-based security progressive hardening defense when untrusted code executes threat boundary principle YAGNI security"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1967,"cache_creation_input_tokens":547,"cache_read_input_tokens":17497,"output_tokens":497,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":547},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1967,"output_tokens":497,"cache_read_input_tokens":17497,"cache_creation_input_tokens":547,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":547,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFkwuYtJSNj6vFrcJvur","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"0696374c-db34-4f6e-894f-dcbd130c246e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:16:47.312Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"c164eccf-e8ae-4ac4-8348-286ede383edf","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LK8qkeyYmqAKS1adpQZV36","type":"tool_result","content":"# Privilege Separation: Threat Defense\n\nBased on the Wikipedia article, privilege separation primarily defends against **security vulnerabilities within programs**. The article states that this technique is \"used to mitigate the potential damage of a computer security vulnerability.\"\n\n## How It Works Against Threats\n\nYes, the protection is most relevant when unprivileged processes can be compromised. The article explains: \"any successful attack against the larger program will gain minimal access, even though the pair of programs will be capable of performing privileged operations.\"\n\nThe mechanism works by dividing a program so that \"a crash in the less privileged part cannot be exploited to gain privileges, merely to cause a denial-of-service attack.\"\n\n## Protection Without Code Execution Risk\n\nThe article doesn't directly address whether privilege separation provides benefits when supervised code cannot execute arbitrary instructions. However, the design principle suggests value remains: by compartmentalizing functionality, the damage scope of *any* compromise in the unprivileged section is inherently limited, regardless of attack vector.\n\nThe core benefit appears architectural—restricting what privileges any single component can access—rather than dependent solely on preventing arbitrary code execution."}]},"uuid":"0404d555-4d40-4cfe-a974-a1e840ba71d5","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:16:48.947Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":80084,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Privilege Separation: Threat Defense\n\nBased on the Wikipedia article, privilege separation primarily defends against **security vulnerabilities within programs**. The article states that this technique is \"used to mitigate the potential damage of a computer security vulnerability.\"\n\n## How It Works Against Threats\n\nYes, the protection is most relevant when unprivileged processes can be compromised. The article explains: \"any successful attack against the larger program will gain minimal access, even though the pair of programs will be capable of performing privileged operations.\"\n\nThe mechanism works by dividing a program so that \"a crash in the less privileged part cannot be exploited to gain privileges, merely to cause a denial-of-service attack.\"\n\n## Protection Without Code Execution Risk\n\nThe article doesn't directly address whether privilege separation provides benefits when supervised code cannot execute arbitrary instructions. However, the design principle suggests value remains: by compartmentalizing functionality, the damage scope of *any* compromise in the unprivileged section is inherently limited, regardless of attack vector.\n\nThe core benefit appears architectural—restricting what privileges any single component can access—rather than dependent solely on preventing arbitrary code execution.","durationMs":4628,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Privilege_separation"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c164eccf-e8ae-4ac4-8348-286ede383edf","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"0bf569a0-8f13-4354-9b5f-64246bf3784d","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014pirFZWFf5HGaxR1223Cfr","type":"tool_result","content":"# Wasmtime's Security Model\n\n## Primary Design Goals\n\nWasmtime protects against threats from **untrusted WebAssembly code** executing in a sandbox. The core protection relies on WebAssembly's inherent design features: \"The callstack is inaccessible\" and \"all accesses within linear memory are checked to ensure they stay in bounds.\"\n\n## Key Protections\n\n**Sandboxing mechanisms:**\n- Memory isolation between instances\n- Type-checked control transfers preventing arbitrary code execution\n- Capability-based filesystem access through WASI\n- Filtering of terminal escape sequences to prevent command injection\n\n**Defense-in-depth layers:**\n- 2GB guard regions preceding linear memory\n- Guard pages on thread stacks\n- Memory zeroing after use\n- Rust's type safety preventing host implementation bugs\n- Control-flow-integrity mechanisms in development\n\n## Assumptions & Limitations\n\nWasmtime assumes a trustworthy host environment. It does **not** protect against:\n- Malicious host code\n- Side-channel attacks beyond basic Spectre mitigations\n- Hardware vulnerabilities unrelated to WebAssembly execution\n\nPlatform-specific limitations exist; for example, macOS may have different guard page behaviors than Linux.\n\n## When to Use\n\nDeploy Wasmtime when running untrusted or third-party compiled WebAssembly code while maintaining application isolation and preventing unauthorized system access."}]},"uuid":"1fa49fe9-1ad9-4c43-8449-44d1e7c970fa","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:16:52.165Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":29125,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Wasmtime's Security Model\n\n## Primary Design Goals\n\nWasmtime protects against threats from **untrusted WebAssembly code** executing in a sandbox. The core protection relies on WebAssembly's inherent design features: \"The callstack is inaccessible\" and \"all accesses within linear memory are checked to ensure they stay in bounds.\"\n\n## Key Protections\n\n**Sandboxing mechanisms:**\n- Memory isolation between instances\n- Type-checked control transfers preventing arbitrary code execution\n- Capability-based filesystem access through WASI\n- Filtering of terminal escape sequences to prevent command injection\n\n**Defense-in-depth layers:**\n- 2GB guard regions preceding linear memory\n- Guard pages on thread stacks\n- Memory zeroing after use\n- Rust's type safety preventing host implementation bugs\n- Control-flow-integrity mechanisms in development\n\n## Assumptions & Limitations\n\nWasmtime assumes a trustworthy host environment. It does **not** protect against:\n- Malicious host code\n- Side-channel attacks beyond basic Spectre mitigations\n- Hardware vulnerabilities unrelated to WebAssembly execution\n\nPlatform-specific limitations exist; for example, macOS may have different guard page behaviors than Linux.\n\n## When to Use\n\nDeploy Wasmtime when running untrusted or third-party compiled WebAssembly code while maintaining application isolation and preventing unauthorized system access.","durationMs":5555,"url":"https://docs.wasmtime.dev/security.html"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"0bf569a0-8f13-4354-9b5f-64246bf3784d","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"0696374c-db34-4f6e-894f-dcbd130c246e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Cri4cQxsxPqVvr9aspsD2E","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"capability-based security progressive hardening defense when untrusted code executes threat boundary principle YAGNI security\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Capability-based security — Grokipedia\",\"url\":\"https://grokipedia.com/page/Capability-based_security\"},{\"title\":\"The Capability-Based Security Model That Makes Privilege Escalation Impossible | by Sohail x Codes | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@sohail_saifii/the-capability-based-security-model-that-makes-privilege-escalation-impossible-8231d679b972\"},{\"title\":\"Capability-based security - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capability-based_security\"},{\"title\":\"Principle 5: Harden your OT boundary | National Cyber Security Centre\",\"url\":\"https://www.ncsc.gov.uk/collection/operational-technology/secure-connectivity/principle-5\"},{\"title\":\"Understanding the YAGNI Principle: A Key to Efficient Software Development - PoisonedYouth TechBlog\",\"url\":\"https://poisonedyouth.github.io/YAGNI_principle\"},{\"title\":\"Securing untrusted code using memory protection key and control flow integrity\",\"url\":\"https://image-ppubs.uspto.gov/dirsearch-public/print/downloadPdf/10810305\"}]\n\nI've performed the web search for your query. Here are the relevant results:\n\n**Capability-Based Security:**\nCapability-based security is a computer security model in which access to system resources is controlled through capabilities—unforgeable tokens that encapsulate a unique object identifier along with specific access rights. This approach enforces the principle of least privilege by limiting access to only those resources explicitly granted via capabilities.\n\n**Progressive Hardening & Defense:**\nThe search results don't contain specific information on \"progressive hardening defense\" as a formal security concept, but related concepts appear. For threat boundaries, many systems have boundaries that become the primary defence against external threats, with hardening strategies focused on modular and replaceable assets.\n\n**Untrusted Code Execution:**\nSeparating untrusted code execution from the remaining trusted code may be difficult and often at high cost of performance overhead.\n\n**YAGNI Principle:**\nYAGNI stands for \"You Aren't Gonna Need It,\" a principle of extreme programming that advises developers to avoid adding functionality unless it's absolutely necessary.\n\nThe search results provide foundational information on these concepts, though they don't specifically connect all of these terms together in the specific context you're querying.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"f036a864-70b9-416b-8d04-883e7750aeda","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:16:59.056Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"capability-based security progressive hardening defense when untrusted code executes threat boundary principle YAGNI security","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01AVRyx5NxTjM4zCaDGtvLhW","content":[{"title":"Capability-based security — Grokipedia","url":"https://grokipedia.com/page/Capability-based_security"},{"title":"The Capability-Based Security Model That Makes Privilege Escalation Impossible | by Sohail x Codes | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@sohail_saifii/the-capability-based-security-model-that-makes-privilege-escalation-impossible-8231d679b972"},{"title":"Capability-based security - Wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capability-based_security"},{"title":"Principle 5: Harden your OT boundary | National Cyber Security Centre","url":"https://www.ncsc.gov.uk/collection/operational-technology/secure-connectivity/principle-5"},{"title":"Understanding the YAGNI Principle: A Key to Efficient Software Development - PoisonedYouth TechBlog","url":"https://poisonedyouth.github.io/YAGNI_principle"},{"title":"Securing untrusted code using memory protection key and control flow integrity","url":"https://image-ppubs.uspto.gov/dirsearch-public/print/downloadPdf/10810305"}]},"I've performed the web search for your query. Here are the relevant results:\n\n**Capability-Based Security:**\nCapability-based security is a computer security model in which access to system resources is controlled through capabilities—unforgeable tokens that encapsulate a unique object identifier along with specific access rights. This approach enforces the principle of least privilege by limiting access to only those resources explicitly granted via capabilities.\n\n**Progressive Hardening & Defense:**\nThe search results don't contain specific information on \"progressive hardening defense\" as a formal security concept, but related concepts appear. For threat boundaries, many systems have boundaries that become the primary defence against external threats, with hardening strategies focused on modular and replaceable assets.\n\n**Untrusted Code Execution:**\nSeparating untrusted code execution from the remaining trusted code may be difficult and often at high cost of performance overhead.\n\n**YAGNI Principle:**\nYAGNI stands for \"You Aren't Gonna Need It,\" a principle of extreme programming that advises developers to avoid adding functionality unless it's absolutely necessary.\n\nThe search results provide foundational information on these concepts, though they don't specifically connect all of these terms together in the specific context you're querying."],"durationSeconds":11.535977874999865,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"0696374c-db34-4f6e-894f-dcbd130c246e","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
