{"parentUuid":"861c1b29-fceb-4bc6-a3b7-10d860ce2069","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_014K9n9jKqoFtjyQ2WhpH5RW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RWhuzwiioH4TKdNt868few","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://github.com/openssh/openssh-portable/blob/master/README.privsep","prompt":"What is the stated purpose of privilege separation in OpenSSH? What exactly is the threat: a bug/vulnerability in the network-facing code being exploited to run attacker code in the unprivileged process. Quote the key sentences about what privsep contains."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4303,"cache_read_input_tokens":18044,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4303,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFkyLvthtrnGvtsZxQJj","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"fbf99a4d-b3a9-4dd8-a351-2c58903e1c5b","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:17:04.524Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"fbf99a4d-b3a9-4dd8-a351-2c58903e1c5b","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_014K9n9jKqoFtjyQ2WhpH5RW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_016ocwBgwEnck68AM7eqquJW","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/security_kernel","prompt":"What is NIST's definition of a security kernel and the reference monitor concept? What are the requirements (mediate all access, protected from modification/tamper-proof, verifiable)?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4303,"cache_read_input_tokens":18044,"output_tokens":410,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4303},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":410,"cache_read_input_tokens":18044,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4303,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4303,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFkyLvthtrnGvtsZxQJj","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"3ac575ae-b37c-498b-a313-ac48b7632e04","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:17:05.660Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"fbf99a4d-b3a9-4dd8-a351-2c58903e1c5b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RWhuzwiioH4TKdNt868few","type":"tool_result","content":"# Privilege Separation in OpenSSH\n\n**Stated Purpose:**\nThe README describes privsep as \"a method in OpenSSH by which operations that require root privilege are performed by a separate privileged monitor process. Its purpose is to prevent privilege escalation by containing corruption to an unprivileged process.\"\n\n**The Threat Model:**\nThe document implies the threat is exploitation of the network-facing code. If an attacker compromises the unprivileged sshd process through a vulnerability, the damage is contained because that process lacks root privileges and operates in a restricted chroot environment.\n\n**Key Containment Mechanism:**\nThe critical sentence states: \"Its purpose is to prevent privilege escalation by containing corruption to an unprivileged process.\"\n\nThis architecture isolates the vulnerable component—the process handling untrusted network input—from root-level system access, limiting the impact of successful exploitation."}]},"uuid":"4ce3eca2-6943-4aaf-8ac5-c0d2cdd275d7","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:17:09.551Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":263604,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Privilege Separation in OpenSSH\n\n**Stated Purpose:**\nThe README describes privsep as \"a method in OpenSSH by which operations that require root privilege are performed by a separate privileged monitor process. Its purpose is to prevent privilege escalation by containing corruption to an unprivileged process.\"\n\n**The Threat Model:**\nThe document implies the threat is exploitation of the network-facing code. If an attacker compromises the unprivileged sshd process through a vulnerability, the damage is contained because that process lacks root privileges and operates in a restricted chroot environment.\n\n**Key Containment Mechanism:**\nThe critical sentence states: \"Its purpose is to prevent privilege escalation by containing corruption to an unprivileged process.\"\n\nThis architecture isolates the vulnerable component—the process handling untrusted network input—from root-level system access, limiting the impact of successful exploitation.","durationMs":4807,"url":"https://github.com/openssh/openssh-portable/blob/master/README.privsep"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"fbf99a4d-b3a9-4dd8-a351-2c58903e1c5b","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"3ac575ae-b37c-498b-a313-ac48b7632e04","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016ocwBgwEnck68AM7eqquJW","type":"tool_result","content":"# NIST's Security Kernel Definition\n\nAccording to NIST SP 800-53 Rev. 5 (citing CNSSI 4009-2015), a security kernel comprises \"Hardware, firmware, and software elements of a trusted computing base implementing the reference monitor concept.\"\n\n## Three Core Requirements\n\nThe definition specifies three essential characteristics:\n\n1. **Access Mediation**: The security kernel must intercept and control all system access attempts, serving as the enforcement point for security policies.\n\n2. **Protection from Modification**: It must be shielded against unauthorized changes or tampering that could compromise its integrity.\n\n3. **Verifiable Correctness**: The security kernel's implementation must be subject to verification and validation to ensure it functions as designed without flaws.\n\nThese requirements work together to establish the security kernel as a trustworthy foundation for system security, ensuring that no access bypasses security controls and that the kernel itself remains secure and reliable."}]},"uuid":"3b8e16ff-ac02-4866-8ae9-d15d2d4d106e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:17:12.823Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":45486,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# NIST's Security Kernel Definition\n\nAccording to NIST SP 800-53 Rev. 5 (citing CNSSI 4009-2015), a security kernel comprises \"Hardware, firmware, and software elements of a trusted computing base implementing the reference monitor concept.\"\n\n## Three Core Requirements\n\nThe definition specifies three essential characteristics:\n\n1. **Access Mediation**: The security kernel must intercept and control all system access attempts, serving as the enforcement point for security policies.\n\n2. **Protection from Modification**: It must be shielded against unauthorized changes or tampering that could compromise its integrity.\n\n3. **Verifiable Correctness**: The security kernel's implementation must be subject to verification and validation to ensure it functions as designed without flaws.\n\nThese requirements work together to establish the security kernel as a trustworthy foundation for system security, ensuring that no access bypasses security controls and that the kernel itself remains secure and reliable.","durationMs":6981,"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/security_kernel"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"3ac575ae-b37c-498b-a313-ac48b7632e04","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"3b8e16ff-ac02-4866-8ae9-d15d2d4d106e","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a78d82338f3aeef1a","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01E196KsN6PhDQ8rAe4JgR27","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have authoritative sourcing across all four research areas. Here is my synthesis and recommendation.\n\n---\n\n# Yogi supervisor isolation: timing decision\n\n## Bottom line\n\n**Defer the process-split + WASM upgrade. Do NOT do it before M4.** The in-process reference monitor remains *honest* through bounded, declarative self-modification, because none of the three reference-monitor properties (tamper-proof, always-invoked, verifiable) are violated by code that only mutates declarative data via a pure `apply()` and never executes attacker- or model-influenced instructions in the supervisor's address space. The upgrade's actual threat — in-address-space hijack of control flow — does not exist at M4. It appears the moment the **executor runs model-generated or external-tool code**. That is the correct, principled trigger.\n\nThe earlier gate said \"self-modification OR native/model-generated code execution, whichever comes first.\" The research says those are *not* the same event, and the gate conflated them. The honest boundary is the **second** clause, not the first.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Reference-monitor criteria: when does \"in-process tamper-proof\" actually break?\n\nAnderson's reference-validation mechanism (and its NIST/Orange-Book lineage) requires three things, summarized as NEAT: **N**on-bypassable, **E**valuable/verifiable, **A**lways-invoked, **T**amper-proof ([Wikipedia: Reference monitor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reference_monitor); [NIST CSRC: security kernel](https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/security_kernel); [NIST SP 800-53 AC-25 reference monitor control]).\n\nThe load-bearing word is **tamper-proof**: \"an attacker can undermine the mechanism itself and hence violate the security policy\" if it fails ([Wikipedia: Reference monitor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reference_monitor)). Tampering is an *active* verb — it presupposes an agent that can **issue instructions** to overwrite the monitor's code/state, redirect its control flow, or forge its decisions. In a shared address space, that capability comes from exactly one source: **the supervised code being able to execute arbitrary (or attacker-steered) machine instructions** — via a memory-safety bug, code injection, or by *being* attacker-authored native code.\n\nThis is the precise answer to your nuance. In-process \"tamper-proof\" is **not** violated by \"self-modification\" in the abstract. It is violated specifically by **in-address-space execution of attacker- or model-influenced code**. Declarative self-mod has neither:\n\n- The being edits **closed-enum genome fields** (prompt/policy strings, skill ids) — *data*, not instructions.\n- The edit goes through a **pure `apply()`** the supervisor (and you) wrote and can audit — this is the monitor *mediating* a write, which is its job, not a breach of it. CLAUDE.md's invariant that `MutationKind` is closed and `apply` matches exhaustively with no `_ =>` arm is itself the structural enforcement of \"evaluable\" + \"non-bypassable.\"\n- No model output is ever compiled, `eval`'d, or jumped to. The model's influence terminates as *bytes in a string field*, which only ever flow back through the proposer prompt — never through an instruction pointer.\n\nSo all three properties survive: the monitor still mediates every genome write (always-invoked), the closed enum makes it analyzable (verifiable), and nothing in-process can rewrite the monitor because nothing in-process runs untrusted instructions (tamper-proof holds *given the M4 constraint*).\n\nThe honesty condition is therefore a **capability claim, not a structural one**: in-process is honest *exactly while the supervised code cannot execute instructions the supervisor didn't write*.\n\n## 2. Privilege separation: what a separate process actually buys you\n\nOpenSSH privsep is the canonical case, and its threat model is explicit: its purpose is \"to prevent privilege escalation by **containing corruption to an unprivileged process**\" ([openssh README.privsep](https://github.com/openssh/openssh-portable/blob/master/README.privsep)). Provos's design ([CITI tech report / privsep paper](http://www.citi.umich.edu/u/provos/papers/privsep.pdf); [Wikipedia: Privilege separation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Privilege_separation)) targets one specific event: a **bug in network-facing code is exploited to run attacker-controlled code** in the unprivileged process. The separate monitor ensures \"any successful attack against the larger program will gain minimal access\" and \"a crash in the less privileged part cannot be exploited to gain privileges, merely to cause a denial-of-service.\"\n\nThe entire value proposition is conditioned on **\"corruption\" being possible** — i.e., on the supervised side being hijackable into running arbitrary instructions. The defense is *containment of a code-execution compromise across a memory boundary the compromised code cannot cross* (separate virtual address spaces; one process's failure doesn't reach another's memory — [arxiv 2306.08127, in-process vs. process isolation](https://arxiv.org/html/2306.08127v2)).\n\n**If the supervised code cannot execute arbitrary instructions, there is no \"corruption\" to contain, and the separate-process boundary defends against a threat that isn't present.** That is precisely Yogi at M4. Process-splitting now would be buying OpenSSH's defense for a server that doesn't yet parse any untrusted input.\n\n## 3. Wasmtime/process-split: cost, the minimum that holds, and what's overkill\n\n**(a) Process split + IPC.** Manual privsep is acknowledged to take \"considerable effort\" even for OpenSSH ([Provos paper](http://www.citi.umich.edu/u/provos/papers/privsep.pdf)). For Yogi you'd add: a stable serialization boundary for every supervisor call (budget debit, reaper verdict, kill-switch), an IPC transport (Unix domain socket on macOS), a watchdog/liveness protocol between the two processes, and crash/restart semantics for the out-of-band reaper. IPC carries real overhead from context switching and crossing the boundary ([arxiv 2306.08127](https://arxiv.org/html/2306.08127v2)). The *benefit* of this work is zero until something on the supervised side can be hijacked.\n\n**(b) Wasmtime for tool/executor code.** Wasmtime is the right tool for the *real* boundary. Its model is exactly \"running untrusted or third-party compiled WebAssembly while preventing unauthorized system access,\" via bounds-checked linear memory, an inaccessible callstack, type-checked control transfers, and **capability-based filesystem access through WASI** ([Wasmtime security](https://docs.wasmtime.dev/security.html)). For resource bounds, the minimum that holds is **epoch-based interruption** (cheap, periodic, sufficient for \"stop runaway tool code\") rather than **fuel** (deterministic but instrumented per-op and \"significantly more expensive\") — epoch is generally faster and is the recommended default unless you need deterministic accounting ([Wasmtime Config docs](https://docs.wasmtime.dev/api/wasmtime/struct.Config.html); [Wasmtime epoch/fuel guidance](https://docs.wasmtime.dev/api/wasmtime/)). Note macOS guard-page behavior differs from Linux ([Wasmtime security](https://docs.wasmtime.dev/security.html)) — a reason to do this deliberately at the boundary, not preemptively.\n\n**What's overkill for a single-machine research build:** doing both *now*; fuel when epoch suffices; full WASI filesystem capability plumbing before any tool actually touches the filesystem; and hardware in-process isolation schemes (MPK/CFI, TRust ~7.5% runtime overhead — [USENIX TRust](https://www.usenix.org/conference/usenixsecurity23/presentation/bang)) which solve a problem (untrusted code that *must* share an address space) Yogi doesn't have, since the executor can simply run in WASM or a child process.\n\n## 4. The principled trigger\n\nYes — there is a clean trigger formulation, and it's the OpenSSH/Wasmtime threat boundary made literal:\n\n> **Upgrade to (process-split supervisor + Wasmtime-sandboxed executor) the moment the executor is about to run any code that is model-generated, externally-fetched, or otherwise not authored-and-reviewed by the operator — before the first such execution, never after, and not before.**\n\nThis is honest because it commits the upgrade to the exact event that makes in-process dishonest (in-address-space execution of attacker/model-influenced instructions — §1, §2), and not to the *name* \"self-modification.\" Bounded declarative self-mod sits safely on the in-process side of that line.\n\n---\n\n## Recommendation (concrete)\n\n**Defer.** Keep the supervisor in-process through M4. Land the process-split + Wasmtime sandbox as the **first gated work item of the executor milestone**, before the executor's first untrusted execution.\n\n**Encode the trigger as a hard, testable gate** (in keeping with CLAUDE.md's invariants-as-tests discipline): the executor crate must not be able to invoke any \"run code\" path while the supervisor is in-process — make it a compile-time or startup assertion that pairs `Executor` with `OutOfProcessSupervisor + WasmSandbox`. That converts the written trigger into machinery, the same way `MutationKind` being closed converts \"no forbidden mutations\" into a compile error.\n\n**To remain honest in-process, M4 MUST NOT:**\n1. Compile, `eval`, link, `dlopen`, or jump to any string/bytes the model produced (model output stays *data* in closed-enum genome fields).\n2. Add any `MutationKind` whose `apply` path executes, spawns, or shells out to genome-derived content — `apply()` stays pure and total over the closed enum (no `_ =>`).\n3. Let a genome field become a code path: no prompt/policy/skill-id field may be interpreted as a command, plugin path, script, or dynamic dispatch target into operator-trusted execution.\n4. Introduce the executor running tools, native plugins, or fetched code under the in-process supervisor — that is the boundary; crossing it *is* the trigger.\n5. Relabel any model-influenced mutation as `DirectUserIntent` (the existing no-launder invariant — independently required, and it also keeps the provenance that the trigger relies on).\n\nIf all five hold, the in-process reference monitor's tamper-proof / always-invoked / verifiable properties are genuinely intact at M4, and the isolation upgrade is correctly scheduled at the executor boundary rather than paid for early against an absent threat.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n- [Reference monitor — Wikipedia (NEAT properties, tamper-proof)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reference_monitor)\n- [NIST CSRC glossary — security kernel](https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/security_kernel)\n- [Privilege separation — Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Privilege_separation)\n- [OpenSSH README.privsep (threat = containing corruption)](https://github.com/openssh/openssh-portable/blob/master/README.privsep)\n- [Provos et al., \"Preventing Privilege Escalation\" (OpenSSH privsep design)](http://www.citi.umich.edu/u/provos/papers/privsep.pdf)\n- [Wasmtime security model](https://docs.wasmtime.dev/security.html)\n- [Wasmtime Config docs (epoch vs. fuel)](https://docs.wasmtime.dev/api/wasmtime/struct.Config.html)\n- [Wasmtime embedding API (interruption guidance)](https://docs.wasmtime.dev/api/wasmtime/)\n- [In-process vs. process isolation for unsafe Rust (arxiv 2306.08127)](https://arxiv.org/html/2306.08127v2)\n- [TRust in-process isolation overhead figures (USENIX Security '23)](https://www.usenix.org/conference/usenixsecurity23/presentation/bang)"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1069,"cache_read_input_tokens":22347,"cache_creation":{"ep